Currently 6.1.

I see very little chance of the exchange rate breaking out of the status quo of between 6 and 7 CNY. The exchange rate has not dipped below 6 in recent memory, and while it had exceeded 7 as recently as earlier this year, obviously a lot has happened between the US and China in the past several months, accelerated by the spread of COVID-19 that has only worsened the US-China relationship and caused a mass rethinking of global trade and global supply chains. With the election of Biden, who may have a more practical approach to the important relationship than his predecessor, there may be some room for upward movement in the exchange rate, but anything significant seems highly unlikely.

Biden taking Michigan. Plus China has done some pretty aggressive things reigning in the Ant financial IPO, making me think that they don't want meaningful FX weakness during this period as well.

It is almost inconceivable that the Dollar-Yuan ratio would be above 8, since it has not been that high since 2006. Additionally, the ratio has not been below 6 since 2018, even with the recent downswings. After the US election the Yuan will likely either go up if Biden wins or down if Trump wins. It seems a little more likely that Biden will win, so I would imagine that the Yuan will stay between 6 and 7, but it could push up above 7.

According to Bloomberg, in the past 5-years the yuan has not dipped below CNY 6 nor has it risen above CNY 7.(1) While Trump, who will still be in office on Nov 13 regardless of the election outcome, has vowed to hold China accountable for its role in the COVID crisis I think it unlikely that he will attempt to renew the trade war with China given the current fixation on domestic issues. Accordingly, I think the yuan will remain stable between its current valuation of 6-7 CNY.

The comparatively high probability for 7-8 stems from the possibility of a global risk-off episode (due to new lockdowns and/or a contested US election) inducing a USD-rally, pushing the CNY/USD slightly above 7 (similar to earlier this year).

US government and EU are trying to increase the value of the yuan to reduce the competitive advantage of China on the world market, while China is trying to do the opposite. With the US involved in their election process beyond November 13, we expect the currency to roughly remain constant. When running a time series analysis, there is roughly a 90% probability that the currency value will remain in its current 6-7 CNY bracket. As the currency value is closer to the bracket above (i.e. 7-8), we estimate that there is a higher chance that it will move up rather than down.

What will be the end-of-day closing value for the U.S. dollar against the Chinese yuan on 13 November 2020? This is a very difficult moment in history. The pandemic has had severe impact on human life, with more than 200,000 Americans dying from COVID-19 or COVID-19 complications. The United States and the rest of the world are in times of uncertainty, which has individual citizens as well as major corporations concerned; “roughly half of all companies in the S&P 500 index have withdrawn earnings guidance, noted Donald Calcagni, chief investment officer with Mercer Advisors, and ‘the few who haven’t, are afraid to” (Riquier, 2020). The world is at a crossroads of what to do. Even with uncertainty, there is a fair amount of data for the U.S. dollar against the Chinese yuan. According to the stock and research company, Macrotrends, the U.S. dollar has had a consistent value compared to the Chinese yuan. From 2008 through the present, the exchange rate of Chinese Yuan to the U.S. Dollar has been valued, at the years close, between 6.00 to 7.00. Even with a worldwide pandemic, the data is consistent. I am 98% sure that at the end of the year, the U.S. dollar and Chinese yuan exchange rate will be between 6.00 to 7.00. The final 2% is between 7.00 to 8.00. Trading Economics. (2020). Currencies. Trading Economics. Retrieved from: https://tradingeconomics.com/forecast/currency Macrotrends. (2020). Dollar Yuan Exchange Rate-35 Year Historical Chart. Macrotrends. Retrieved from: https://www.macrotrends.net/2575/us-dollar-yuan-exchange-rate-historical-chart Riguier, A. (2020, July 10). Forget earnings season. What’s the rest of 2020 going to look like. Market Watch. Retrieved from: https://www.marketwatch.com/story/forget-earnings-season-whats-the-rest-of-2020-going-to-look-like-2020-07-04

The Chinese economy has grown significantly in recent years driving the use of the yuan abroad (Tan, 2020). Three areas where the US dollar is defeats the yuan are stability, liquidity, and security, driving the dollar to continue to be the worlds foremost currency (Amadeo, 2020) Throughout summer 2020 in which the US economy fell due to the Covid-19 pandemic, a rise in the yuan to dollar exchange from 7.01 to 6.7 was observed (Macrotrends, 2020). Currently well within the 6.0 -7.0 range at 6.6947 as of 09:30 on 10/11/ 2020, average daily variances are well below 0.1% (Bloomberg, 2020). Therefore, with the exception of a large unforeseen market shift, current trends indicate that shifting out of the 6.0-7.0 range would take months (Bloomberg, 2020).

The closing value for the USD against the CNY has steadily decreased over the last 6 months and is has been resting at approximately 6.79 for since the beginning of October. It has not been above 7.00 since July 2020. A combination of the presidential election coming up, the holidays, and increasing COVID restriction, I do not think the USD will strengthen until the spring against the CNY.

US trade deficit of August 2020 was about 67bn USD, the highest since 2008 and the third-highest on record. It seems Trumponomics don't really root out that very problem, not even with a trade war. Not to mention the budget deficit - I heard congress glued together some form of preliminary budget until end of 2020. The double deficit issue is back on the agenda, and it's apparently worse than ever. However, my rationale is that with markets getting increasingly nervous and volatile over the next two weeks, investors will be looking for a shelter for capital - the US Dollar will increasingly appear as a safe and stable haven, a pattern that has been repeatedly observed in past crises. As absurd as it factually is.

The Chinese yuan has not gone below 6 since 2003 and it is not likely to. In the same time period the last time the yuan was greater that 7 to 1 was in March 2008 which was before the 2008 recession where the global GDP declined by 5.1%. There were additional points where the yuan was valued over 7 to 1 recently and we are now on a trend heading back down towards 6 to 1.

The current value of the U.S. dollar (USD) against the Chinese yuan is 1 USD to 6.79 yuan. (XE, 2020). In the past year, the yuan has fluctuated between 7.15 and 6.75, meaning it is only slightly below its highest value. COVID seems to have little impact on the value of the yuan, which gained 0.1 against the dollar in the first week of March (XE, 2020). It is surprising that the yuan has been so stable, considering recent actions against Huawei and general global resentment against China for the coronavirus. In fact, in the last ten years, it has only fluctuated between 6.05 and 7.15, its lowest value (which occurred in May of this year).

The value of the yuan has seen the impact from an escalation in the protracted U.S.-Sino trade war, as well as an adjustment and the impact of the ongoing tensions within Hong Kong. At some point, and if the Chinese market ever become more transparent, I would expect to see the yuan drop again. We’re waiting to see the next yuan adjustment.

seasonal, bell-curves in the fall/winter. While they differed slightly year to year, generally, this seemed a significant trend to consider in my forecast. Observando el grafico de Yuan vs Dolar disponible por Google, podemos notar que históricamente en los últimos años el valor se encuentra estancado entre 6-7 yuan/dolar por lo que corresponde asignarle la mayor probabilidad a este tramo, la cual es muy posible siguiendo los patrones históricos. Por otro lado, de igual forma un par de veces el precio ha estado sobre 7 yuan/dolar por lo que asigno un 15% de probabilidad a que se ubique en esta posición, pero de igual forma es una probabilidad baja, ya que en tan poco tiempo tendencia que ocurrir algún suceso importante para que existiera una subida de este calibre del precio yuan/dolar. Por otro lado, existe una probabilidad baja de que el dolar se devalúe y el valor sea de 6 o menos, esto ya que China se encuentra liderando la búsqueda de la vacuna contra el covid en comparación con USA, entonce la creación de esta generaría una alza del valor Chino comparado con el Estadounidense. Además, China se encuentra en transición a su moneda virtual, por lo que también generaría un mayor movimiento económico y subiría el valor del Yuan. Pongo poca probabilidad ya que es poco tiempo hasta el 12 de noviembre y es muy difícil una baja de este nivel, pero es pequeñamente posible.

The Yuan continues to be supported by the equity bull market in China and a generally more gloomy outlook for the US Dollar. The Financial Times ran articles on the reasons for dollar weakness on Monday and today (https://www.ft.com/content/e6352387-5704-4e44-9b79-22ae87039e59) arguing that the risks in the US outweigh: - unemployment benefits may not be extended after July, which could crush the US economy - Covid-19 is spreading quickly and does not seem to get under control before winter flu season - Election year and risks associated with democratic horse trading in case of a victory - Lack of demand for dollar swap facility by other central banks A lot of bearish coverage can sometimes be a sign of a turnaround, but currently there are no signs that bets against the dollar are getting crowded..

May 30= 7.1364CNY/$ In the last 5 years it's gone from a high of 6.2 to a low of 7.16. Since the onset of the pandemic it has gone from a high of 6.86 to the low of 7.16. It appears to be managed lower in response to the pandemic and the desire to increase exports. My assumption is that China would prefer a band around 7 and above to encourage exports to keep factories busy as they recover.

Since the value of the CNY is determined by the Chinese gov't, and is "allowed to float in a narrow margin around a fixed base rate determined with reference to a basket of world currencies" [1], it seems like this is more a question of how China wants to be perceived against the US in the fall or if there is a trading advantage to a stronger / weaker currency. Currently it is trading around 7 CNY to the USD [2].

In times of financial stress, the US Dollar used to appreciate (counter-intuitively) versus major currencies in the world due to a "safe-haven" argument and because financial markets' liquidity is an important argument for speculative investors. On the other hand, China has a track record for administrating their currency within a bandwidth and most of the time weakening their currency (currency manipulation) verbally in order to make products more competitive on export markets. The total effect may be around zero. With a special situation of an ongoing tariff war and an unprecedented increment in US public debt, (probably) slowing growth in China's currency reserves and not least disruptions in world trade/repatriation of some production in the wake of SARS-CoV-2, the total effect on USDCNY is hard to tell. To me it depends on whether "the West" will continue to gather behind the US with one accord despite political tensions with the current White House administration (POTUS 45) in the future, and how hard the landing of the Chinese export oriented economic model and the distress in the Chinese financial system will turn out. My guess is (armed conflicts with Chinese involvement excluded), the CNY will further depreciate by between 5 to 10 per cent, with a final exchange rate of about 7,60 CNY per USD on 13 November 2020.
